/*
https://leetcode.com/problems/last-stone-weight/description/

You are given an array of integers stones where stones[i] is the weight of the ith stone.

We are playing a game with the stones. On each turn, we choose the heaviest two stones and smash them together. Suppose the heaviest two stones have weights x and y with x <= y. The result of this smash is:

If x == y, both stones are destroyed, and
If x != y, the stone of weight x is destroyed, and the stone of weight y has new weight y - x.
At the end of the game, there is at most one stone left.

Return the weight of the last remaining stone. If there are no stones left, return 0.

 

Example 1:

Input: stones = [2,7,4,1,8,1]
Output: 1
Explanation: 
We combine 7 and 8 to get 1 so the array converts to [2,4,1,1,1] then,
we combine 2 and 4 to get 2 so the array converts to [2,1,1,1] then,
we combine 2 and 1 to get 1 so the array converts to [1,1,1] then,
we combine 1 and 1 to get 0 so the array converts to [1] then that's the value of the last stone.
Example 2:

Input: stones = [1]
Output: 1
 

Constraints:

1 <= stones.length <= 30
1 <= stones[i] <= 1000

*/


/*
Since each turn requires choosing the two heaviest stones, 
I need a data structure that can efficiently give me the maximum value. 
A max heap is a good fit. I insert all stones into the heap, 
then while at least two stones remain, I remove the top two.
If they are different, I insert their difference back. 
At the end, if the heap is empty I return 0, otherwise I return the remaining stone. 
The time complexity is O(n log n) and space complexity is O(n).

Time Complexity

Let n be the number of stones.

Building heap:

O(n log n)

Each smash removes two stones and may insert one back:

O(log n)

Total:

O(n log n)
Space Complexity

We store all stones in the heap:

O(n)
*/


import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public int lastStoneWeight(int[] stones) {
        // Max heap: largest stone comes first
        PriorityQueue<Integer> maxHeap = new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> b - a);

        // Add all stones into max heap
        for (int stone : stones) {
            maxHeap.offer(stone);
        }

        // Continue until at most one stone is left
        while (maxHeap.size() > 1) {
            // y is the heaviest stone
            int y = maxHeap.poll();

            // x is the second heaviest stone
            int x = maxHeap.poll();

            // If weights are different, put the remaining stone back
            if (y != x) {
                maxHeap.offer(y - x);
            }
        }

        // If heap is empty, no stone left
        // Otherwise return the last stone weight
        return maxHeap.isEmpty() ? 0 : maxHeap.poll();
    }
}
